design_1.name: Lynx
design_1.description: Czech Republic proposal; a fictional substance in the novel Továrna na absolutno by Karel Čapek.

design_2.name: Eridanus
design_2.description: The name was originally Arabic: آخر النهر āẖir an-nahr ('river's end').

design_3.name: Cassiopeia
design_3.description: Apparently first applied to η Cassiopeiae in the Skalnate Pleso Atlas of the Heavens published in 1950, but is not known prior to that.

design_4.name: Hydra
design_4.description: From the Chinese name 張 Zhāng ('extended net').

design_6.name: Cancer
design_6.description: The name was originally Arabic: الزبانى az-zubāná ('the claws').

design_7.name: Canis Major
design_7.description: The name is originally from Arabic: عذارى ʿaḏārá ('virgins'). In the Calendarium of Al Achsasi Al Mouakket, it is designated أول العذاري awwil al-ʿaḏāriyy, translated into Latin as Prima Virginum ('first virgin').

design_8.name: Boötes
design_8.description: From the Chinese name 玄戈 Xuángē ('sombre lance').

design_9.name: Taurus
design_9.description: The name is originally from Arabic: عين ʿayn ('eye') and was reviewed and adopted by the Working Group on Star Names.

design_10.name: Lyra
design_10.description: Nanjing proposal; Xihe is the goddess of the Sun in Chinese mythology. The star also represents the earliest Chinese astronomers and makers of calendars.

design_11.name: Phoenix
design_11.description: A traditional name in the culture of the Wardaman people of the Northern Territory of Australia.

design_12.name: Virgo
design_12.description: Vindemiatrix is Latin for '(female) grape gatherer'

design_13.name: Sagitta
design_13.description: Iraqi proposal; named after Uruk, an ancient city of Sumer and Babylonia in Mesopotamia.

design_14.name: Serpens
design_14.description: From Arabic: عنق الحية ʿunuq al-ḥayya ('the serpent's neck'), called Cor Serpentis ('Heart of the Serpent') in Latin.

design_15.name: Scorpius
design_15.description: The traditional name of the β Scorpii system has been rendered Akrab and Elakrab, derived (like Acrab) from Arabic: العقرب al-ʿaqrab ('the scorpion').

design_16.name: Centaurus
design_16.description: Pitcairn Islands proposal. Aklen means 'we/us' in the Pitkern language.

design_17.name: Reticulum
design_17.description: Brazilian proposal; named after the indigenous Tupi people.

design_18.name: Canes Venatici
design_18.description: Irish proposal. The aunt of the warrior Fionn mac Cumhaill of Irish legend.

design_19.name: Puppis
design_19.description: Moroccan proposal; named after Tislit Lake and means 'the bride' in the Amazigh language. Associated with a heartbroken girl in legend.

design_20.name: Ophiuchus
design_20.description: Bangladeshi proposal; means 'darkness' in the Bengali language.

design_21.name: Draco
design_21.description: From the Chinese name 天乙 Tiānyǐ or 天一 Tiānyī ('the Celestial Great One'), a deity in Taoism.

design_22.name: Auriga
design_22.description: Israeli proposal; means 'world' or 'universe' in the Hebrew language.

design_23.name: Gemini
design_23.description: Traditional name, also called Tejat Posterior.

design_25.name: Crux
design_25.description: Acrux is a modern contraction of the Bayer designation, coined in the 19th century, but which entered into common use only by the mid-20th century.

design_26.name: Carina
design_26.description: Bolivian proposal; means 'Milky Way' in Guarani.

design_27.name: Pegasus
design_27.description: Bulgarian proposal; named after Tengri, the god early Bulgars worshiped.

design_28.name: Lacerta
design_28.description: Lithuanian proposal; means 'peace' in the Lithuanian language.

design_29.name: Vela
design_29.description: Traditionally, this name also applied to Velorum (Regor).

design_30.name: Delphinus
design_30.description: The name appeared in Piazzi's Palermo Star Catalogue in 1814, added by Niccolò Cacciatore as a prank along with Rotanev (β Delphini); 'Sualocin' is Nicolaus, the Latin form of Italian: Niccolò ('Nicholas'), spelt backwards.

design_31.name: Leo
design_31.description: Pakistani proposal; an Urdu literary term meaning 'a small lamp or flame'.

design_32.name: Piscis Austrinus
design_32.description: Sri Lankan proposal; means 'peace' in the Sinhala language.

design_33.name: Orion
design_33.description: Traditional name from Arabic: سیف الجبار sayf al-jabbār, literally 'saif ('sword') of the giant'.

design_34.name: Sagittarius
design_34.description: From Arabic: عين الرامي ʿayn ar-rāmī ('eye of the archer').

design_35.name: Tucana
design_35.description: Cook Islands proposal; means a large mystical black pearl in the Cook Islands Māori language.

design_36.name: Hercules
design_36.description: Liechtenstein proposal; named after a bright and visible butterfly in the local dialect of Triesenberg.

design_37.name: Andromeda
design_37.description: The name was originally Arabic: الذيل aḏ-ḏayl (the train, lit. 'the tail').

design_38.name: Antlia
design_38.description: Colombian proposal; named after a mythical village from the novel Cien anos de soledad (One Hundred Years of Solitude) by Gabriel García Márquez.

design_39.name: Pavo
design_39.description: Designated 'Peacock' (after the constellation) by His Majesty's Nautical Almanac Office for the Royal Air Force in the 1930s.

design_40.name: Pisces
design_40.description: Singaporean proposal; the name is Latin for 'little lion'.

design_42.name: Dorado
design_42.description: South African proposal; means 'star' in the Sesotho, SeTswana and SePedi languages.

design_43.name: Perseus
design_43.description: Danish proposal; named after the Norse mythological realm of fire Muspelheim.

design_44.name: Cetus
design_44.description: Tanzanian proposal; named after Dalbergia melanoxylon, a tree whose ebony wood is used for musical instruments.

design_45.name: Corona Borealis
design_45.description: Romanian proposal; named after Moldoveanu Peak, the highest peak in Romania.

design_46.name: Monoceros
design_46.description: Portuguese proposal; ancient name for Lusitania, the region where most of Portugal is situated.

design_47.name: Aquarius
design_47.description: Hong Kong proposal; named after Lion Rock, a culturally important lion-shaped peak.

design_48.name: Apus
design_48.description: New Zealand proposal; word for a local plant that produces orange fruit in the Māori language.

design_49.name: Grus
design_49.description: Gabonese proposal; means 'all that is beautiful' in the Myene language.

design_50.name: Fornax
design_50.description: Malaysian proposal; means 'diamond' in the Malay language.

design_51.name: Camelopardalis
design_51.description: German proposal; named after Mago National Park, a national park in Ethiopia noted for its giraffes (Camelopardalis is Latin for 'giraffe').

design_52.name: Ara
design_52.description: Peruvian proposal; a character in the story Way to the Sun by Abraham Valdelomar.

design_53.name: Leo Minor
design_53.description: Albanian proposal; named after the Illyrians, the people from whom Albanians are descended and what they call themselves.

design_54.name: Crater
design_54.description: Honduran proposal; one of the Maya Hero Twins who became the Sun in K'iche' Maya mythology.

design_55.name: Triangulum
design_55.description: Finnish proposal; the name of hell or the underworld in Finnic mythology.
